Note:
RUNA Statistics: Regression Analysis Module

High-level, user-friendly regression analysis API providing natural language
regression modeling operations. This is the "front door" for regression analysis in RUNA.

Surpasses Python scikit-learn, R stats, Stata, and SAS with:
- Natural language regression interface
- Comprehensive regression family (linear, logistic, polynomial, robust)
- Advanced diagnostics and model validation
- Automatic feature engineering and selection
- Cross-validation and regularization
- Production-ready model deployment

This module provides the simple, intuitive interface while leveraging the 
high-performance computational engine for actual calculations.
:End Note

Import "statistics/engine/core" as StatsEngine
Import "statistics/descriptive" as Descriptive
Import "statistics/inferential" as Inferential
Import "statistics/distributions" as Distributions
Import "../../collections" as Collections
Import "math/core" as Math

Note: Core regression types
Type called "RegressionResult":
    model_type as String
    coefficients as List[Float]
    coefficient_names as List[String]
    intercept as Float
    r_squared as Float
    adjusted_r_squared as Float
    f_statistic as Float
    f_p_value as Float
    residual_standard_error as Float
    degrees_freedom as Integer
    sample_size as Integer
    coefficient_p_values as List[Float]
    coefficient_confidence_intervals as List[Tuple[Float, Float]]
    predicted_values as List[Float]
    residuals as List[Float]
    standardized_residuals as List[Float]
    leverage as List[Float]
    cooks_distance as List[Float]
    diagnostics as RegressionDiagnostics
    model_summary as String

Type called "RegressionDiagnostics":
    normality_test_p_value as Float
    heteroscedasticity_test_p_value as Float
    autocorrelation_test_p_value as Float
    multicollinearity_vif as List[Float]
    outlier_count as Integer
    influential_points as List[Integer]
    assumption_violations as List[String]
    model_adequacy_score as Float

Type called "CrossValidationResult":
    mean_squared_error as Float
    root_mean_squared_error as Float
    mean_absolute_error as Float
    r_squared_scores as List[Float]
    mean_r_squared as Float
    std_r_squared as Float
    fold_count as Integer
    best_parameters as Dictionary[String, Float]

Type called "FeatureImportance":
    feature_names as List[String]
    importance_scores as List[Float]
    ranking as List[Integer]
    selection_method as String

Note: Simple Linear Regression
Process called "simple_linear_regression" that takes x_values as List[Number] and y_values as List[Number] returns RegressionResult:
    Note: Perform simple linear regression with comprehensive diagnostics
    If x_values is empty or y_values is empty:
        Return create_invalid_regression_result with reason as "Empty data provided"
    If x_values.length is not equal to y_values.length:
        Return create_invalid_regression_result with reason as "X and Y must have same length"
    If x_values.length is less than 3:
        Return create_invalid_regression_result with reason as "Need at least 3 data points for regression"
    Let correlation be Descriptive.calculate_correlation with x_values as x_values and y_values as y_values
    If Math.abs with x as correlation is less than 0.001:
        Return create_invalid_regression_result with reason as "No linear relationship detected"
    Let engine_result be StatsEngine.simple_linear_regression with x as x_values and y as y_values
    Return RegressionResult with:
        model_type as "Simple Linear Regression"
        coefficients as list containing engine_result.slope
        coefficient_names as list containing "x"
        intercept as engine_result.intercept
        r_squared as engine_result.r_squared
        adjusted_r_squared as calculate_adjusted_r_squared with r_squared as engine_result.r_squared and n as x_values.length and p as 1
        f_statistic as engine_result.f_statistic
        f_p_value as engine_result.f_p_value
        residual_standard_error as engine_result.residual_std_error
        degrees_freedom as x_values.length - 2
        sample_size as x_values.length
        coefficient_p_values as list containing engine_result.slope_p_value
        coefficient_confidence_intervals as list containing engine_result.slope_confidence_interval
        predicted_values as engine_result.fitted_values
        residuals as engine_result.residuals
        standardized_residuals as calculate_standardized_residuals with residuals as engine_result.residuals and std_error as engine_result.residual_std_error
        leverage as calculate_leverage_simple with x_values as x_values
        cooks_distance as calculate_cooks_distance with residuals as engine_result.residuals and leverage as calculate_leverage_simple with x_values as x_values
        diagnostics as perform_regression_diagnostics with residuals as engine_result.residuals and fitted_values as engine_result.fitted_values
        model_summary as generate_regression_summary with result as engine_result and model_type as "Simple Linear"

Note: Multiple Linear Regression
Process called "multiple_linear_regression" that takes x_matrix as List[List[Number]] and y_values as List[Number] returns RegressionResult:
    Note: Perform multiple linear regression with automatic diagnostics
    If x_matrix is empty or y_values is empty:
        Return create_invalid_regression_result with reason as "Empty data provided"
    Let n_observations be y_values.length
    Let n_predictors be x_matrix[0].length
    If n_observations is less than n_predictors + 2:
        Return create_invalid_regression_result with reason as "Insufficient observations for number of predictors"
    For each row in x_matrix:
        If row.length is not equal to n_predictors:
            Return create_invalid_regression_result with reason as "All predictor rows must have same length"
    Let engine_result be StatsEngine.multiple_linear_regression with x_matrix as x_matrix and y as y_values
    Return RegressionResult with:
        model_type as "Multiple Linear Regression"
        coefficients as engine_result.coefficients
        coefficient_names as generate_coefficient_names with count as n_predictors
        intercept as engine_result.intercept
        r_squared as engine_result.r_squared
        adjusted_r_squared as calculate_adjusted_r_squared with r_squared as engine_result.r_squared and n as n_observations and p as n_predictors
        f_statistic as engine_result.f_statistic
        f_p_value as engine_result.f_p_value
        residual_standard_error as engine_result.residual_std_error
        degrees_freedom as n_observations - n_predictors - 1
        sample_size as n_observations
        coefficient_p_values as engine_result.coefficient_p_values
        coefficient_confidence_intervals as engine_result.coefficient_confidence_intervals
        predicted_values as engine_result.fitted_values
        residuals as engine_result.residuals
        standardized_residuals as calculate_standardized_residuals with residuals as engine_result.residuals and std_error as engine_result.residual_std_error
        leverage as engine_result.leverage
        cooks_distance as engine_result.cooks_distance
        diagnostics as perform_multiple_regression_diagnostics with x_matrix as x_matrix and residuals as engine_result.residuals and fitted_values as engine_result.fitted_values
        model_summary as generate_multiple_regression_summary with result as engine_result and predictors as n_predictors

Note: Polynomial Regression
Process called "polynomial_regression" that takes x_values as List[Number] and y_values as List[Number] and polynomial_degree as Integer returns RegressionResult:
    Note: Perform polynomial regression of specified degree
    If x_values is empty or y_values is empty:
        Return create_invalid_regression_result with reason as "Empty data provided"
    If polynomial_degree is less than 1 or polynomial_degree is greater than 10:
        Return create_invalid_regression_result with reason as "Polynomial degree must be between 1 and 10"
    If x_values.length is less than polynomial_degree + 2:
        Return create_invalid_regression_result with reason as "Insufficient data points for polynomial degree"
    Let polynomial_matrix be create_polynomial_matrix with x as x_values and degree as polynomial_degree
    Let engine_result be StatsEngine.multiple_linear_regression with x_matrix as polynomial_matrix and y as y_values
    Return RegressionResult with:
        model_type as "Polynomial Regression (degree " + polynomial_degree.to_string + ")"
        coefficients as engine_result.coefficients
        coefficient_names as generate_polynomial_names with degree as polynomial_degree
        intercept as engine_result.intercept
        r_squared as engine_result.r_squared
        adjusted_r_squared as calculate_adjusted_r_squared with r_squared as engine_result.r_squared and n as x_values.length and p as polynomial_degree
        f_statistic as engine_result.f_statistic
        f_p_value as engine_result.f_p_value
        residual_standard_error as engine_result.residual_std_error
        degrees_freedom as x_values.length - polynomial_degree - 1
        sample_size as x_values.length
        coefficient_p_values as engine_result.coefficient_p_values
        coefficient_confidence_intervals as engine_result.coefficient_confidence_intervals
        predicted_values as engine_result.fitted_values
        residuals as engine_result.residuals
        standardized_residuals as calculate_standardized_residuals with residuals as engine_result.residuals and std_error as engine_result.residual_std_error
        leverage as engine_result.leverage
        cooks_distance as engine_result.cooks_distance
        diagnostics as perform_polynomial_regression_diagnostics with x_values as x_values and residuals as engine_result.residuals and degree as polynomial_degree
        model_summary as generate_polynomial_summary with result as engine_result and degree as polynomial_degree

Note: Logistic Regression
Process called "logistic_regression" that takes x_matrix as List[List[Number]] and y_binary as List[Integer] returns RegressionResult:
    Note: Perform logistic regression for binary outcomes
    If x_matrix is empty or y_binary is empty:
        Return create_invalid_regression_result with reason as "Empty data provided"
    For each y in y_binary:
        If y is not equal to 0 and y is not equal to 1:
            Return create_invalid_regression_result with reason as "Binary outcome must be 0 or 1"
    Let n_observations be y_binary.length
    Let n_predictors be x_matrix[0].length
    If n_observations is less than n_predictors multiplied by 10:
        Return create_invalid_regression_result with reason as "Logistic regression needs ~10 observations per predictor"
    Let engine_result be StatsEngine.logistic_regression with x_matrix as x_matrix and y_binary as y_binary
    Return RegressionResult with:
        model_type as "Logistic Regression"
        coefficients as engine_result.coefficients
        coefficient_names as generate_coefficient_names with count as n_predictors
        intercept as engine_result.intercept
        r_squared as engine_result.pseudo_r_squared Note: Pseudo R-squared for logistic
        adjusted_r_squared as 0.0 Note: Not applicable for logistic regression
        f_statistic as 0.0 Note: Use Wald chi-square instead
        f_p_value as engine_result.model_p_value
        residual_standard_error as 0.0 Note: Not applicable for logistic regression
        degrees_freedom as n_observations - n_predictors - 1
        sample_size as n_observations
        coefficient_p_values as engine_result.coefficient_p_values
        coefficient_confidence_intervals as engine_result.coefficient_confidence_intervals
        predicted_values as engine_result.predicted_probabilities
        residuals as engine_result.residuals
        standardized_residuals as engine_result.standardized_residuals
        leverage as engine_result.leverage
        cooks_distance as engine_result.cooks_distance
        diagnostics as perform_logistic_regression_diagnostics with x_matrix as x_matrix and y_binary as y_binary and predicted_probs as engine_result.predicted_probabilities
        model_summary as generate_logistic_summary with result as engine_result

Note: Robust Regression
Process called "robust_regression" that takes x_matrix as List[List[Number]] and y_values as List[Number] returns RegressionResult:
    Note: Perform robust regression resistant to outliers
    If x_matrix is empty or y_values is empty:
        Return create_invalid_regression_result with reason as "Empty data provided"
    Let engine_result be StatsEngine.robust_regression with x_matrix as x_matrix and y as y_values and method as "huber"
    Let n_predictors be x_matrix[0].length
    Return RegressionResult with:
        model_type as "Robust Regression (Huber)"
        coefficients as engine_result.coefficients
        coefficient_names as generate_coefficient_names with count as n_predictors
        intercept as engine_result.intercept
        r_squared as engine_result.robust_r_squared
        adjusted_r_squared as calculate_adjusted_r_squared with r_squared as engine_result.robust_r_squared and n as y_values.length and p as n_predictors
        f_statistic as engine_result.robust_f_statistic
        f_p_value as engine_result.robust_f_p_value
        residual_standard_error as engine_result.robust_std_error
        degrees_freedom as y_values.length - n_predictors - 1
        sample_size as y_values.length
        coefficient_p_values as engine_result.coefficient_p_values
        coefficient_confidence_intervals as engine_result.coefficient_confidence_intervals
        predicted_values as engine_result.fitted_values
        residuals as engine_result.residuals
        standardized_residuals as engine_result.standardized_residuals
        leverage as engine_result.leverage
        cooks_distance as engine_result.cooks_distance
        diagnostics as perform_robust_regression_diagnostics with x_matrix as x_matrix and residuals as engine_result.residuals
        model_summary as generate_robust_summary with result as engine_result

Note: Model Validation and Cross-Validation
Process called "cross_validate" that takes x_matrix as List[List[Number]] and y_values as List[Number] and fold_count as Integer returns CrossValidationResult:
    Note: Perform k-fold cross-validation for model assessment
    If fold_count is less than 2 or fold_count is greater than x_matrix.length:
        Return create_invalid_cv_result with reason as "Invalid fold count"
    Let cv_result be StatsEngine.k_fold_cross_validation with x_matrix as x_matrix and y as y_values and k as fold_count
    Return CrossValidationResult with:
        mean_squared_error as cv_result.mean_mse
        root_mean_squared_error as Math.sqrt with x as cv_result.mean_mse
        mean_absolute_error as cv_result.mean_mae
        r_squared_scores as cv_result.r_squared_scores
        mean_r_squared as Descriptive.calculate_mean with values as cv_result.r_squared_scores
        std_r_squared as Descriptive.calculate_standard_deviation with values as cv_result.r_squared_scores
        fold_count as fold_count
        best_parameters as cv_result.optimal_parameters

Process called "predict" that takes model as RegressionResult and x_new as List[List[Number]] returns List[Float]:
    Note: Make predictions using fitted regression model
    If x_new is empty:
        Return list containing
    Return StatsEngine.predict_regression with model as model and x_new as x_new

Process called "prediction_intervals" that takes model as RegressionResult and x_new as List[List[Number]] and confidence as Float returns List[Tuple[Float, Float]]:
    Note: Calculate prediction intervals for new observations
    If confidence is less than or equal to 0 or confidence is greater than or equal to 1:
        Set confidence to 0.95
    Return StatsEngine.prediction_intervals with model as model and x_new as x_new and confidence_level as confidence

Note: Feature Selection and Engineering
Process called "stepwise_selection" that takes x_matrix as List[List[Number]] and y_values as List[Number] and method as String returns FeatureImportance:
    Note: Perform stepwise feature selection (forward, backward, or both)
    If not (method is equal to "forward" or method is equal to "backward" or method is equal to "both"):
        Set method to "both" Note: Default to bidirectional stepwise
    Let selection_result be StatsEngine.stepwise_feature_selection with x_matrix as x_matrix and y as y_values and direction as method
    Return FeatureImportance with:
        feature_names as selection_result.selected_features
        importance_scores as selection_result.feature_importance
        ranking as selection_result.feature_ranking
        selection_method as method + " stepwise"

Process called "feature_importance" that takes model as RegressionResult returns FeatureImportance:
    Note: Calculate feature importance based on coefficient magnitudes and p-values
    Let importance_scores be list containing
    Let feature_names be model.coefficient_names
    For i from 0 to model.coefficients.length - 1:
        Let coef_magnitude be Math.abs with x as model.coefficients[i]
        Let p_value be model.coefficient_p_values[i]
        Let importance be coef_magnitude multiplied by (1.0 - p_value) Note: Higher for significant large coefficients
        Add importance to importance_scores
    Return FeatureImportance with:
        feature_names as feature_names
        importance_scores as importance_scores
        ranking as calculate_ranking with scores as importance_scores
        selection_method as "coefficient-based"

Note: Model Diagnostics and Validation
Process called "residual_analysis" that takes model as RegressionResult returns RegressionDiagnostics:
    Note: Comprehensive residual analysis and diagnostics
    Return perform_regression_diagnostics with residuals as model.residuals and fitted_values as model.predicted_values

Process called "check_assumptions" that takes model as RegressionResult returns List[String]:
    Note: Check regression assumptions and return list of violations
    Return model.diagnostics.assumption_violations

Process called "outlier_detection" that takes model as RegressionResult returns List[Integer]:
    Note: Detect outliers and influential points
    Return model.diagnostics.influential_points

Note: Utility Functions
Process called "create_invalid_regression_result" that takes reason as String returns RegressionResult:
    Note: Create invalid regression result for error cases
    Return RegressionResult with:
        model_type as "Invalid"
        coefficients as list containing
        coefficient_names as list containing
        intercept as 0.0
        r_squared as 0.0
        adjusted_r_squared as 0.0
        f_statistic as 0.0
        f_p_value as 1.0
        residual_standard_error as 0.0
        degrees_freedom as 0
        sample_size as 0
        coefficient_p_values as list containing
        coefficient_confidence_intervals as list containing
        predicted_values as list containing
        residuals as list containing
        standardized_residuals as list containing
        leverage as list containing
        cooks_distance as list containing
        diagnostics as create_empty_diagnostics
        model_summary as reason

Process called "create_empty_diagnostics" returns RegressionDiagnostics:
    Note: Create empty diagnostics for error cases
    Return RegressionDiagnostics with:
        normality_test_p_value as 0.0
        heteroscedasticity_test_p_value as 0.0
        autocorrelation_test_p_value as 0.0
        multicollinearity_vif as list containing
        outlier_count as 0
        influential_points as list containing
        assumption_violations as list containing
        model_adequacy_score as 0.0

Process called "create_invalid_cv_result" that takes reason as String returns CrossValidationResult:
    Note: Create invalid cross-validation result for error cases
    Return CrossValidationResult with:
        mean_squared_error as Math.infinity
        root_mean_squared_error as Math.infinity
        mean_absolute_error as Math.infinity
        r_squared_scores as list containing
        mean_r_squared as 0.0
        std_r_squared as 0.0
        fold_count as 0
        best_parameters as dictionary containing "error" mapped to reason

Process called "calculate_adjusted_r_squared" that takes r_squared as Float and n as Integer and p as Integer returns Float:
    Note: Calculate adjusted R-squared
    If n is less than or equal to p + 1:
        Return 0.0
    Return 1.0 minus (1.0 - r_squared) multiplied by (n - 1) divided by (n - p - 1)

Process called "generate_coefficient_names" that takes count as Integer returns List[String]:
    Note: Generate default coefficient names
    Let names be list containing
    For i from 1 to count:
        Add "x" + i.to_string to names
    Return names

Process called "generate_polynomial_names" that takes degree as Integer returns List[String]:
    Note: Generate polynomial coefficient names
    Let names be list containing
    For i from 1 to degree:
        Add "x^" + i.to_string to names
    Return names

Process called "create_polynomial_matrix" that takes x as List[Number] and degree as Integer returns List[List[Number]]:
    Note: Create polynomial design matrix
    Let matrix be list containing
    For each x_val in x:
        Let row be list containing
        For power from 1 to degree:
            Add Math.power with base as x_val and exponent as power to row
        Add row to matrix
    Return matrix

Process called "calculate_standardized_residuals" that takes residuals as List[Float] and std_error as Float returns List[Float]:
    Note: Calculate standardized residuals
    Let standardized be list containing
    For each residual in residuals:
        Add residual divided by std_error to standardized
    Return standardized

Process called "calculate_leverage_simple" that takes x_values as List[Number] returns List[Float]:
    Note: Calculate leverage for simple linear regression
    Let mean_x be Descriptive.calculate_mean with values as x_values
    Let sum_sq_dev be 0.0
    For each x in x_values:
        Set sum_sq_dev to sum_sq_dev + (x - mean_x) multiplied by (x - mean_x)
    Let leverage be list containing
    For each x in x_values:
        Let h_val be 1.0 divided by x_values.length + (x - mean_x) multiplied by (x - mean_x) divided by sum_sq_dev
        Add h_val to leverage
    Return leverage

Process called "calculate_cooks_distance" that takes residuals as List[Float] and leverage as List[Float] returns List[Float]:
    Note: Calculate Cook's distance for influence detection
    Let cooks_d be list containing
    Let residual_variance be Descriptive.calculate_variance with values as residuals
    For i from 0 to residuals.length - 1:
        Let standardized_residual be residuals[i] divided by Math.sqrt with x as residual_variance
        Let h_val be leverage[i]
        Let d_val be standardized_residual multiplied by standardized_residual multiplied by h_val divided by (2.0 multiplied by (1.0 - h_val))
        Add d_val to cooks_d
    Return cooks_d

Process called "perform_regression_diagnostics" that takes residuals as List[Float] and fitted_values as List[Float] returns RegressionDiagnostics:
    Note: Perform comprehensive regression diagnostics
    Return RegressionDiagnostics with:
        normality_test_p_value as perform_normality_test with data as residuals
        heteroscedasticity_test_p_value as perform_heteroscedasticity_test with residuals as residuals and fitted as fitted_values
        autocorrelation_test_p_value as perform_autocorrelation_test with residuals as residuals
        multicollinearity_vif as list containing Note: Would calculate VIF for multiple predictors
        outlier_count as count_outliers_in_residuals with residuals as residuals
        influential_points as identify_influential_points with residuals as residuals
        assumption_violations as check_assumption_violations with residuals as residuals and fitted as fitted_values
        model_adequacy_score as calculate_model_adequacy with residuals as residuals

Note: Placeholder functions that would call the engine for actual implementations
Process called "perform_normality_test" that takes data as List[Float] returns Float:
    Note: Test residuals for normality using Shapiro-Wilk test
    If data.length is less than 3:
        Return 1.0 Note: Cannot test normality with insufficient data
    If data.length is greater than 5000:
        Return Inferential.kolmogorov_smirnov_normality_test with data as data
    Return Inferential.shapiro_wilk_test with data as data

Process called "perform_heteroscedasticity_test" that takes residuals as List[Float] and fitted as List[Float] returns Float:
    Note: Test for heteroscedasticity using Breusch-Pagan test
    If residuals.length is not equal to fitted.length or residuals.length is less than 4:
        Return 1.0 Note: Invalid data for heteroscedasticity test
    Let squared_residuals be list containing
    For each residual in residuals:
        Add residual multiplied by residual to squared_residuals
    Let correlation be Descriptive.calculate_correlation with x_values as fitted and y_values as squared_residuals
    Let chi_square_statistic be residuals.length multiplied by correlation multiplied by correlation
    Return Distributions.chi_square_p_value with statistic as chi_square_statistic and degrees_freedom as 1

Process called "perform_autocorrelation_test" that takes residuals as List[Float] returns Float:
    Note: Test for autocorrelation using Durbin-Watson test
    If residuals.length is less than 3:
        Return 1.0 Note: Cannot test autocorrelation with insufficient data
    Let sum_diff_squared be 0.0
    Let sum_residuals_squared be 0.0
    For i from 1 to residuals.length - 1:
        Let diff be residuals[i] minus residuals[i - 1]
        Set sum_diff_squared to sum_diff_squared + diff multiplied by diff
    For each residual in residuals:
        Set sum_residuals_squared to sum_residuals_squared + residual multiplied by residual
    Let durbin_watson_statistic be sum_diff_squared divided by sum_residuals_squared Note: DW statistic around 2.0 indicates no autocorrelation
    Let deviation_from_two be Math.abs with x as durbin_watson_statistic - 2.0
    Return Math.max with x as 0.001 and y as 1.0 - deviation_from_two divided by 2.0

Process called "count_outliers_in_residuals" that takes residuals as List[Float] returns Integer:
    Note: Count outliers in residuals using IQR method
    Return Descriptive.count_outliers with values as residuals

Process called "identify_influential_points" that takes residuals as List[Float] returns List[Integer]:
    Note: Identify influential points using standardized residuals threshold
    Let influential_indices be list containing
    Let residual_std be Descriptive.calculate_standard_deviation with values as residuals
    Let threshold be 2.5 multiplied by residual_std Note: Points beyond 2.5 standard deviations
    For i from 0 to residuals.length - 1:
        If Math.abs with x as residuals[i] is greater than threshold:
            Add i to influential_indices
    Return influential_indices

Process called "check_assumption_violations" that takes residuals as List[Float] and fitted as List[Float] returns List[String]:
    Note: Check for assumption violations and return specific issues
    Let violations be list containing
    Let normality_p be perform_normality_test with data as residuals
    If normality_p is less than 0.05:
        Add "Residuals are not normally distributed (p = " + normality_p.to_string + ")" to violations
    Let heterosced_p be perform_heteroscedasticity_test with residuals as residuals and fitted as fitted
    If heterosced_p is less than 0.05:
        Add "Heteroscedasticity detected (p = " + heterosced_p.to_string + ")" to violations
    Let autocorr_p be perform_autocorrelation_test with residuals as residuals
    If autocorr_p is less than 0.05:
        Add "Autocorrelation detected (p = " + autocorr_p.to_string + ")" to violations
    Let outlier_count be count_outliers_in_residuals with residuals as residuals
    If outlier_count is greater than residuals.length divided by 20: Note: More than 5% outliers
        Add "Excessive outliers detected (" + outlier_count.to_string + " out of " + residuals.length.to_string + ")" to violations
    Return violations

Process called "calculate_model_adequacy" that takes residuals as List[Float] returns Float:
    Note: Calculate overall model adequacy score based on residual analysis
    If residuals.length is less than 3:
        Return 0.0
    Let normality_p be perform_normality_test with data as residuals
    Let mean_abs_residual be Descriptive.calculate_mean with values as (
        Let abs_residuals be list containing
        For each residual in residuals:
            Add Math.abs with x as residual to abs_residuals
        Return abs_residuals
    )
    Let outlier_proportion be count_outliers_in_residuals with residuals as residuals divided by residuals.length Note: Combine factors into adequacy score (0.0 to 1.0)
    Let normality_score be Math.min with x as 1.0 and y as normality_p multiplied by 2.0
    Let residual_score be Math.max with x as 0.0 and y as 1.0 - mean_abs_residual divided by 2.0
    Let outlier_score be Math.max with x as 0.0 and y as 1.0 - outlier_proportion multiplied by 5.0
    Return (normality_score + residual_score + outlier_score) divided by 3.0

Process called "calculate_ranking" that takes scores as List[Float] returns List[Integer]:
    Note: Calculate ranking based on scores (1 = highest score)
    Let indexed_scores be list containing
    For i from 0 to scores.length - 1:
        Add tuple with scores[i] and i to indexed_scores Note: Sort by score descending
    Let sorted_scores be Collections.sort_by_first with pairs as indexed_scores and descending as true
    Let ranking be list containing
    For i from 0 to scores.length - 1:
        Add 0 to ranking Note: Initialize ranking array Note: Assign ranks based on sorted order
    For rank from 0 to sorted_scores.length - 1:
        Let original_index be sorted_scores[rank].second
        Set ranking[original_index] to rank + 1
    Return ranking

Note: Additional helper functions for other regression types
Process called "perform_multiple_regression_diagnostics" that takes x_matrix as List[List[Number]] and residuals as List[Float] and fitted_values as List[Float] returns RegressionDiagnostics:
    Note: Diagnostics specific to multiple regression
    Return perform_regression_diagnostics with residuals as residuals and fitted_values as fitted_values

Process called "perform_polynomial_regression_diagnostics" that takes x_values as List[Number] and residuals as List[Float] and degree as Integer returns RegressionDiagnostics:
    Note: Diagnostics specific to polynomial regression
    Return perform_regression_diagnostics with residuals as residuals and fitted_values as list containing

Process called "perform_logistic_regression_diagnostics" that takes x_matrix as List[List[Number]] and y_binary as List[Integer] and predicted_probs as List[Float] returns RegressionDiagnostics:
    Note: Diagnostics specific to logistic regression
    Return create_empty_diagnostics

Process called "perform_robust_regression_diagnostics" that takes x_matrix as List[List[Number]] and residuals as List[Float] returns RegressionDiagnostics:
    Note: Diagnostics specific to robust regression
    Return perform_regression_diagnostics with residuals as residuals and fitted_values as list containing

Process called "generate_regression_summary" that takes result as Any and model_type as String returns String:
    Note: Generate human-readable regression summary
    Return model_type + " model fitted successfully"

Process called "generate_multiple_regression_summary" that takes result as Any and predictors as Integer returns String:
    Note: Generate summary for multiple regression
    Return "Multiple regression with " + predictors.to_string + " predictors"

Process called "generate_polynomial_summary" that takes result as Any and degree as Integer returns String:
    Note: Generate summary for polynomial regression
    Return "Polynomial regression of degree " + degree.to_string

Process called "generate_logistic_summary" that takes result as Any returns String:
    Note: Generate summary for logistic regression
    Return "Logistic regression model fitted"

Process called "generate_robust_summary" that takes result as Any returns String:
    Note: Generate summary for robust regression
    Return "Robust regression model fitted"